Audio-Kit Algorithms Documentation

This document hosts documentation of algorithms.

Algorithms memory pool allocation

In addition to the algorithm parameters described below, a new parameter called ramType has been added. This parameter allows you to choose the preferred memory pool for most algorithms, especially those that consume a lot of memory or for which the memory type significantly impacts CPU load. The available memory pools are:

  • Tightly Coupled Memory (TCM): The fastest memory.
  • Internal RAM: Medium performance memory.
  • External RAM: The largest memory, if present.

The algorithms memory allocator will first attempt to allocate memory in the specified pool. If the requested memory pool is unavailable (due to platform limitations or insufficient remaining memory), it will fall back to another memory pool.

When an audio design is running, the mem2 command displays the detailed memory consumption for each algorithm in each memory pool, indicating where memory allocation was requested and where it was actually allocated.

Note: Each algorithm has a generic memory part (for handle, config, etc.) and a specific memory part (e.g., internal audio buffers or any other memory needed for processing). The ramType parameter only affects the allocation of the specific memory part. In order to change the pool of the generic please refer to this chapter.

AcousticBF

The AcousticBF software library is fully described in the documentation called AcousticBF_Library.chm located inside the folder:

Middlewares/ST/STM32_Audio/STM32_AcousticBF_Library/Documentation of the package.

However, the AudioChain wrapper adds a feature called Mixer that can be enabled from the parameter mixer_enable. This feature allows to mix the output of the highly directive beamforming with one of the input microphones signals.

It is functional with both presets called ACOUSTIC_BF_TYPE_STRONG & ACOUSTIC_BF_TYPE_ASR_READY. It doesnt work with presets called ACOUSTIC_BF_TYPE_CARDIOID_DENOISE & ACOUSTIC_BF_TYPE_CARDIOID_BASIC.

Two parameters need to be tuned when activated:

  1. tLowDb: Low threshold for mixing with omni microphone. If level is inferior to this threshold, then only omni microphone in output signal. Unit is dB.

  2. tHighDb: High threshold for mixing with omni microphone. If level is superior to this threshold, then only processed data in output signal. Unit is dB.

  • In between both thresholds, a linear gain is applied as function of the energy of the first raw microphone signal.

  • To tune it, please do as follow:

    • Connect a message viewer to the Msg output pin,

    • Set the control_refresh to a value higher than 1 (it is counting the number of frames before refreshing the control data),

    • Run the device in the sound environment it should support and set the thresholds as function of the value measured.

CIC

Overview

The CIC (Cascaded Integrator-Comb) module is designed to perform decimation of Pulse Density Modulation (PDM) input streams to Pulse Code Modulation (PCM) output streams. The module supports multi-channel interleaved PDM input and produces interleaved PCM output. The decimation ratio is an integer value, and the input sampling frequency divided by the output sampling frequency multiplied by 8 must be an integer value.

Limitations

  • Sampling Frequency Ratio: The ratio of input sampling frequency to output sampling frequency is an integer value.

  • Decimation: Decimation is performed by accumulation of byte packets, ensuring that the input sampling frequency divided by the output sampling frequency multiplied by 8 is an integer value.

  • SINC order: up to 5

Inputs/Outputs

Inputs

  • Input Stream:

    • A single audio input stream.
    • Accepts only PDM (LSB first or MSB first) format with multi-channel interleaved by bytes.
    • Supports all PDM frequencies allowed by AudioChain.

  • order:

    • SINC filter order. Maximum is 5

  • rbs:

    • Right bit shift of the output samples.
    • Helps to guarantee no saturation in case of 16-bit samples
    • Can be used as a gain control if saturation is allowed.

Output

  • Output Stream:

    • A single audio output stream.
    • Produces PCM output in int16 or int32 format
    • In case of multichannel, data is interleaved.
    • ratio of input and output sampling frequency must be an integer value.
    • Ensure that the input sampling frequency divided by the output sampling frequency multiplied by 8 is an integer value (fsIn / (fsOut * 8) ).

Configuration Parameters

There are two types of parameters:

  1. Format information for conversion retrieved from the input and output pins:

    • sampling frequency
    • number of channels
    • PDM format (MSB or LSB)
    • PCM format (int16 or int32)

  2. Configuration parameters:

    • SINC filter order
    • right bit shift of the output samples

DeInterleave

Overview

This document outlines the specifications for an audio processing block that deinterleaves an input stream into a several output streams. The output streams will contain all requested channels from the input stream.

Please note that the primary function of this algorithm is to split a single multichannel input stream into several output streams. It is not designed to alter the interleaving format of the individual samples within the stream; such transformations are the responsibility of the SFC (Sample Format Conversion) algorithm.

Features

  • Multiple Outputs: Generate several audio output streams from a single input.

  • Channel selection: Supports output streams with different number of channels.

  • Deinterleaving: interleaved inputs into several output streams.

  • Format conversion: Ability to change data format thanks to the SFC algorithm.

Inputs/Outputs

Inputs

  • Input Stream: Single audio multichannel input stream.

  • Source Format: The current format of the input audio samples is known thanks to the input pin that is aware of its own properties including data type and interleaving (see SFC documentation).

  • Target Format: The desired format for the output audio samples is known thanks to the output pins that are aware of their own properties data type and interleaving (SFC documentation).

Output

  • Interleaved Audio Streams: Several output streams with different number of channels; the sum of number of channels of output streams must be equal to the number of channels of input stream.

Processing Steps

Note: this algorithm encapsulates the SFC for input & output management. Please refer to its documentation.

  1. Input Handling: The block receives audio from an input multichannel stream.

  2. Deinterleaving & format conversion:

  • Channels from the input stream are extracted and copied into the different output streams as requested. Channels selection is done while setting the output pins characteristics.

  • Note: Before the initialization phase, the consistency checks of the algorithm checks that the number of input channels is equal to the sum of all output streams channels.

  • Deinterleave supports following format conversion:

    1. interleaved into non interleaved sample and vice versa.

    2. Can convert from any of this data type to any other within this list: FIXED16, FIXED32, FLOAT, G711.

    3. Can convert input PDM LSB into PDM MSB and vice versa.

  • Deinterleave doesnt support the following format conversion:

    1. It cannot convert PCM to PDM data nor PDM into PCM data (see PDM2PCM algorithm for that).

    2. It cannot convert sampling frequency.

  1. Output Generation:
  • The final output streams are produced with all channels from the input.

Configuration Parameters

The setting of the format conversion is handled by tuning the input & output pins according to the desired characteristics. Please refer to the SFC documentation.

The setting of deinterleaving is also done thru the input and output pins as shown by following figure.

In the example below, the input stream has 3 channels deinterleaved into two streams:

  • The first output has 2 channels.

  • The second output has a single channel.

  • We could also have created three mono output streams.

Faust

Faust algorithms integration in audio-kit.

Faust description

Faust (Functional Audio Stream) is a programming language specifically designed for real-time signal processing and synthesis. Faust is used to create audio applications and plugins for various platforms and standards. The Faust IDE (Integrated Development Environment) is a tool that provides a user-friendly interface for writing, compiling, and testing Faust code. You can build your audio stream programmatically or using the link at https://faustide.grame.fr.

Audio Kit Conversion

Audio Kit can integrate automatic Faust design directly from the .dsp (Faust project). The resource takes place in the folder Middlewares/ST/Audio-Kit/tools/faust. All you need is a .c file generated by the Faust application.

There are two ways to create a Faust Element

Using Web interface:

  • Design your effect on the website :

  • Export the C file! select export -> source -> C.

Using Faust command line interface and the DSP file.

  • You can create a .dsp from the faust code editor by copy/past

  • Download Faust Cli from https://github.com/grame-cncm/faust/releases.

Faust2AC.py is a python file that automatically converts a Faust-ide-c file into an audio kit element.

The tool generates a series of source code you can integrate directly in your project.

In livetune, you will have the same tuning interface and audio will produce the same effect, excepted, that the code will run in the MCU and not on PC

The Faust2AC.py converter is given as an example. It applies some patches on the C code generated by Faust to prevent build issues and generate a glue code.

Limitations

However, there may be issues during the conversion due to bugs in the C generation such as:

  • Syntax incompatibility with the IAR or GCC toolchain that needs manual correction,

  • the converter has been tested with FAUST Version 2.70.3; later ones may come with incompatibilities

  • Huge tables generated that dont fit MCU Memory and Flash specifications, or CPU load not compatible with the MCU specifications.

  • Faust generates a C file with missing headers C (Includes)

  • Faust generated code may consume CPU load not compatible with the MCU specifications. The user MUST ensure that the use case is compatible with the MCU performance.

Elements demo pre-built:

As examples, all algorithms located inside Middlewares/ST/Audio-Kit/tools/faust have been converted directly from examples available on Faust IDE website. There are:

  • phasing/phaser.dsp

  • phasing/flager.dsp

  • reverb/dattorro.dsp

  • dynamic/compressor.dsp

  • and so on

Note that the converter uses source code templates designed for filtering, which is the main use case. In this case there is only one input and one output pin. Default templates are not suitable for source elements (no input pin) or Sink elements (no output pin). Therefore, some adaptation must be done in capability descriptions to be perfectly adapted. For example, if a wave generator is designed and needs to play immediately without modifying the source code templates, the input must be connected to a dummy source element to make the audio chain engine coherencies happy. Please refer to myFaust.livetune in the folder faut for more information.

fBeamforming

Frequency beamformer

.

Overview

This document describes a beamformer that performs processing in the frequency domain.

Beamforming is a signal processing technique used in sensor arrays for directional signal transmission or reception. This spatial filtering process can enhance the signal-to-interference ratio (SIR), which is the power ratio between a signal of interest and given interference signals.

Features

This precise beamformer is called Maximum SIR (Signal to Interference Ratio) beamformer. It is forming beam pattern (or lobes) from different parameters such as:

  • Number of sensors

    • Currently limited to two because the HW available supports 2 microphones.

    • If > 2 Supposed to be linear array.

  • Distance between sensors.

  • Number of bands.

  • a given location of the source of interest.

  • a given positions of potential interferences.

  • Note: In dynamic environments, where the direction of the desired signal or interference may change, adaptive beamforming algorithms could be used, however it is not the case here. The setting is fixed at the initialization phase.

Inputs/Outputs

Inputs

  • Input Stream: Two microphones data streams in the frequency domain.

  • Parameters: See the chapter called Configuration Parameters

Output

  • Output Stream: two opposite antennas in the frequency domain.

Processing Steps

The computation of the beamformer weight is done at the initialization phase. It is a script running on a server that processes the weights from the chosen parameters. Then these weights are loaded on the STM32 flash memory to run the beamformer.

On STM32 side, the processing is:

  • ant1 = mic1 * sirBeamformCoeff_1 + mic2 * sirBeamformCoeff_2

  • ant2 = mic1 * sirBeamformCoeff_2 + mic2 * sirBeamformCoeff_1 for the opposite antenna (second channel)

Configuration Parameters

There are two types of parameters:

  • Input & output streams configuration:

    • Since it is in the frequency domain, there are some constraints to respect. These constraints are detailed inside both WolaFwd & WolaInv algorithms in the chapter called Frequency domain constraints in AudioChain/LiveTune

  • The parameters in the UI:

    • These parameters are the one of a python script that run on a server (either local or distant) which can be set from the preference icon in LiveTune.

    • Part of the parameters are just for analysis such as:

      • uintDb check box.

      • plot_freq which allows to plot the shape of the pattern for a given frequency.

  • Part of the parameters are fixed by the firmware:

    • Mic_nb = 2 because the setup proposed by this package only supports 2 microphone arrays.

    • Bands_nb must be tuned accordingly to the Input & output streams configuration.

  • The parameters that will impact the beam pattern are:

    • In the General tab:

      • Mic_dist expressed in millimeters.

      • Noise_std which is the standard deviation of the background noise inside each sensor.

    • In the Sources tab:

      • The angle value in degrees for the source to point at.

      • The angle value in degrees for the interference where to design a 0.

      • Of course, with a two microphones array, it is useless use many sources or interferences inputs.

When a graph is done and the fBeamforming is properly connected, click the upload button to process the beamformer weights. Hit the start button in LiveTune and give it a try !

To analyze the beam pattern as function of the frequency (see previous figure):

  • Please change the frequency value with the plot_freq slider.

  • Hit the upload button again.

  • It will generate a request to the server that hosts the script.

  • The beam pattern is updated.

How to update the parameters

  1. Set the preferences in LiveTune so that the local server is used as depicted below:

  1. Under the tool folder, please run the script called runServer.sh.
  2. In LiveTune, update the fbeamforming parameter as needed and then hit the Upload icon.

In order to update the cardoid plot, please hit the upload icon again after any parameter update.

fdisjoin

Frequency band extraction; opposite operation is fjoin.

.

Overview

This document details the functionality of an audio processing block designed to operate on audio data that is already in the frequency domain. The blocks purpose is to split a single frequency-domain input stream into several outputs, each containing a specified frequency bands range. This is ideal for applications that require parallel processing of different frequency ranges, such as multiband dynamics processing or frequency-dependent effects routing.

Note: AudioChain frequency domain processing only supports non interleaved floating points data.

Features

  • Frequency-Domain Input: Input data that is already in the frequency domain given a set of frequency sub bands.

  • Frequency-Domain Outputs: Splits the input into multiple outputs, each with a designated set of frequency sub bands range.

  • Customizable Band Ranges: User can define the frequency ranges for each output.

  • Transparent Processing: Ensures no additional transformation or distortion of the frequency-domain data.

Inputs/Outputs

Inputs

  • Input Stream: Single multiband audio stream, each potentially with multiple channels.

  • Output Bands Range indexes: indexes of the lower and higher bands to deliver in the output stream.

Output

  • Output Streams: Multiple multiband output streams, each containing a specific frequency sub bands range from the input stream.

Processing Steps

  • Input Reception: The block receives the frequency-domain audio stream. It has a given number of bands given by the field called nbElements from the input pin.

  • Band Extraction:

    • The data corresponding to each frequency from the specified bands range is copied from the input stream to the proper output stream. The specified frequency indexes must not exceed the input stream bands indexes.

Configuration Parameters

The Customizable Band Ranges are set using both parameters:

  1. begId: index of the first band to extract

  2. endId: index of the last band to extract

  • However, the output stream (acChunk) must be configured accordingly; the nbElements must be equal to (endId -begId +1).

FIR equalizer

Configuration Parameters

  • preset:
    • FIR equalizer has several presets:
      • Acoustic - Folk,
      • Classic,
      • Electronic,
      • Hip Hop,
      • Pop,
      • Rock.
  • firType:
    • linear phase: filter is symmetric; all frequencies are delayed with the same value (firSize/2 samples); best for music signals.
    • minimum phase: filter is not symmetric; delay is minimum but different for each frequency.
  • firSize:
    • the bigger, the more accurate.
    • the smaller, the less memory & MHz consumption.
  • gainInterpolLinear:
    • enabled: response curve interpolation between successive points is linear.
    • disabled: response curve interpolation between successive points is linear in dB.
  • firResponseCurve:
    • User sets filter frequency response
    • Frequency (Hz) in abscissa (log scale), gain (dB) in ordinate,
    • When a point is selected, the user can set an accurate numerical value using frequency/gain_dB boxes below the graph.
    • Remark: the button allows to copy the firResponseCurve graph as an image.

How to add a point in the firResponseCurve curve

Adding a point in the graph is done by shift click on the curve followed by a pointer move (i.e move the mouse).

Grph output pin may be connected to a Graph-Viewer to show theoretical response curve (only when audio is started); it permits for instance to see impact of firType, firSize or gainInterpolLinear (without changing any other parameter) on theoretical response curve accuracy.

WARNING: known limitation

Filter coefficients computation from firResponseCurve consumes a lot of CPU load; thus if user updates filter configuration while the data-flow is running, this processing is shared between successive audio frames so that it consumes around 10% of the max CPU load to leave CPU power to other algos and thus to limit audio data flow issues (underrun/overrun).

Nevertheless, if audio data flow issues appear and remain persistent after FIR-equalizer reinitialization, the workaround is to stop the graph and start it again (or to update FIR-equalizer configuration while the graph is not started).

This CPU load is proportional to firSize and is much bigger for minimum phase than for linear phase firType; thus the worst case is for maximum firSize and minimum phase firType and may last several seconds during which the FIR-equalizer continues to apply old config.

FIR graphic equalizer

Configuration Parameters

  • firType:
    • linear phase: filter is symmetric; all frequencies are delayed with the same value (firSize/2 samples); best for music signals.
    • minimum phase: filter is not symmetric; delay is minimum but different for each frequency.
  • firSize:
    • the bigger, the more accurate.
    • the smaller, the less memory & MHz consumption.
  • gainInterpolLinear:
    • enabled: response curve interpolation between successive points is linear.
    • disabled: response curve interpolation between successive points is linear in dB.
  • centerFrequencyMode:
    • full-automatic center frequency mode: algorithm finds automatically center frequency for every band depending on sampling frequency and number of bands (firstBandCenterFrequency and bandCenterFrequencyStep parameters are not used)
    • semi-automatic center frequency mode: algorithm computes center frequency for every band depending on firstBandCenterFrequency, bandCenterFrequencyStep and number of bands.
    • manual center frequency mode: user sets himself center frequency for every band.

WARNING: in full or semi-automatic mode, when audio is started, center frequencies are sent by FW to LiveTune and thus FW computed values are updated into the graph; when audio is not started, center frequencies are not updated into the graph because audio FW is not running but they will be updated as soon as user will start audio.

  • firstBandCenterFrequency:
    • center frequency of the first band (used only in semi-automatic center frequency mode)
    • this parameter is updated automatically by audio FW in full-automatic center frequency mode
  • bandCenterFrequencyStep:
    • center frequency step in octave unit between 2 successive bands (used only in semi-automatic center frequency mode)
    • this parameter is updated automatically by audio FW in full-automatic center frequency mode
  • firGrEqResponse:
    • Click on button to add a new band, click on to remove a band.
    • in manual center frequency mode, user must set centerFreq value for each band (in automatic modes, it is done automatically by audio FW)
    • in all modes, user must set gain_dB value for each band
  • reorderBands: this check box has no impact in automatic modes (because center frequencies are already correctly ordered by audio FW); in manual center frequency mode, this check box reorders center frequencies in ascending order

Grph output pin may be connected to a Graph-Viewer to show theoretical response curve (only when audio is started); it permits for instance to see impact of firType, firSize or gainInterpolLinear (without changing any other parameter) on theoretical response curve accuracy.

WARNING: known limitation

Filter coefficients computation from firResponseCurve consumes a lot of CPU load; thus if user updates filter configuration while the data-flow is running, this processing is shared between successive audio frames so that it consumes around 10% of the max CPU load to leave CPU power to other algos and thus to limit audio data flow issues (underrun/overrun).

Nevertheless, if audio data flow issues appear and remain persistent after FIR-graphic-equalizer reinitialization, the workaround is to stop the graph and start it again (or to update FIR-graphic-equalizer configuration while the graph is not started).

This CPU load is proportional to firSize and is much bigger for minimum phase than for linear phase firType; thus the worst case is for maximum firSize and minimum phase firType and may last several seconds during which the FIR-graphic-equalizer continues to apply old config.

fjoin

Frequency band concatenation; opposite operation is fdisjoin.

.

Overview

This document describes an audio processing block that concatenates multiple frequency-domain input streams into a single output stream. Each input stream represents a distinct frequency band range, and the FJOIN block combines these bands to form a wider frequency spectrum in the output. This block is essential for applications that involve parallel frequency band processing and require recombination into a full-spectrum signal.

Note: AudioChain frequency domain processing only supports non interleaved floating points data.

Features

  • Frequency-Domain Inputs: Input data streams that are already in the frequency domain and which shouldnt include full spectrum.

  • Frequency-Domain Output: Single output stream that will receive the bands ranges concatenated.

  • Band Ranges Concatenation: All the input bands are joined into the single output.

  • Transparent Processing: Ensures no additional transformation or distortion of the frequency-domain data.

Inputs/Outputs

Inputs

  • Input Streams: Multiple multiband audio stream, each potentially with multiple channels. The order of connection is important, the low bands should be connected first whereas the higher ones should be connected to the latest pins.

Output

  • Output Stream: Single multiband output stream containing all the band ranges concatenated.

Processing Steps

  • Input Reception: The block receives multiple frequency-domain input streams, each representing a different frequency bands range.

  • Bands Concatenation:

    • The full set of frequency bands from the input streams are recombined by order of the input pins. In other words:

      • Lets call Stream0 the stream connected to pin0, Stream1 the stream connected to pin1 and so on.

      • Lets call StreamOut the output stream.

      • The bands from Stream0 are copied to the lowest bands of StreamOut starting from the index 0.

      • Then the bands Stream1 are copied to the following bands of StreamOut starting from the index equal to Stream0 number of bands.

      • And so on .

Configuration Parameters

There is no need for parameters. However, the total number of all input streams bands MUST BE equal to the output stream number of bands. Flowwoing figure provides an example:

  • The acChunk stream connected to fjoin pin0 has 54 bands.

  • The acChunk stream connected to fjoin pin1 has 75 bands.

  • The acChunk stream connected to fjoin output pin has 129 bands.

  • 54+75 = 129! Its all fine

  • However, to create an output stream with a consistent spectrum, the user must take good care of the order of connection otherwise the output signal will be wrong.

.

fnlms

Frequency Normalized-LMS

Overview

This document describes a frequency domain version of the Normalized-LMS algorithm provided in LiveTune. It finds the best FIR filter, so that filtered input matches the reference signal. The process used is the minimization of Least Mean Squares of (Ref - filtered Src). Each sub band has its own adaptive filtering.

Inputs/Outputs

Inputs

  • Src: input data.

  • Ref: reference data

  • Number of Coefficients/taps: It corresponds to the maximal removable echo. echo_length = numTaps / sampling_frequency;

  • Adaptation Step size: It is the step size that controls filter coefficient updates; the biggest, the fastest convergence but the less accurate.

Output

  • Out: output data:

    • It is the filtered input signal.

  • Err: error data

    • It is the (Reference signal filtered input signal).

G711dec

G711 decoder

Features

  • Input: Accepts G711_ALAW & G711_MULAUW PCM format.

  • Output: Accepts only fixed-point 16 bits PCM format

  • Format conversion: Ability to change data format.

Inputs/Outputs

Inputs

  • Input Stream: A single audio input stream.

  • Source Format: The format for the input audio samples is known thanks to the input pin that is aware of its own properties including data type (G711 A-law or G711 mu-law) and interleaving.

Output

  • Output Stream: A single audio output stream.

Processing Steps

  1. Input Handling: input stream is received by the audio processing block.

  2. G711 decoding:

    1. decoding according to input data type.

Configuration Parameters

  • Format information for conversion is retrieved from the pins so that it is up to the user to configure the wires according to his desire (input data type).

G711Enc

G711 encoder

Features

  • Input: Accepts only fixed-point 16 bits PCM format.

  • Output: Accepts G711_ALAW & G711_MULAUW PCM format

  • Format conversion: Ability to change data format.

Inputs/Outputs

Inputs

  • Input Stream: A single audio input stream.

  • Target Format: The desired format for the output audio samples is known thanks to the output pin that is aware of its own properties including data type (G711 A-law or G711 mu-law) and interleaving.

Output

  • Output Stream: A single audio output stream.

Processing Steps

  1. Input Handling: input stream is received by the audio processing block.

  2. G711 encoding:

    1. Encoding according to output data type.

Configuration Parameters

  • Format information for conversion is retrieved from the pins so that it is up to the user to configure the wires according to his desire (output data type).

HPF

High-pass filtering

.

hpf aim is to remove DC component of audio signal; DC may appear with some microphone inputs and may impact some algos behavior, thus it may be necessary to remove this DC component from input signal.

The only hpf configuration parameter is the filter type; hpf uses high-pass filters and several banks of filter with different filter design methods have been included in resample algo, each of these design methods have its pro & cons in terms of MHz/memory consumption (decreasing consumption order: butterworth, chebyshev1/chebyshev2, elliptic), response curve (see https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Signals_and_Systems/Filter_Implementations and https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elliptic_filter for more details).

All these internal filters have been designed with the following constraints:

  • stop frequency: 50 Hz

  • pass frequency: 200 Hz

  • band-pass ripple: +/- 0.10 dB (i.e.all input signal > 200 Hz will have a gain between -0.1 and +0.1 dB)

  • band-stop ripple: -60.00 dB (i.e.all input signal < 50 Hz will have a gain < -60 dB)

IIR equalizer

See https://webaudio.github.io/Audio-EQ-Cookbook/audio-eq-cookbook.html for IIR filter formula description.

Click on button to add a new biquad (i.e.bi-quadratic filter), click on to remove a biquad.

  • biquadSort: sort biquad poles in order of decreasing (up sort) or increasing (down sort) distance to unit circle; see matlab zp2sos order parameter https://mathworks.com/help/signal/ref/zp2sos.html

    • BIQUAD_NO_SORT: keep order of biquads as users definition.

    • BIQUAD_UP_SORT: best for stability (minimize overflow probability).

    • BIQUAD_DOWN_SORT (keep users biquad order)

  • iirType:

    • NOTCH: remove one frequency (gain_dB is not used).

    • PEAKING: amplify of gain_dB one frequency.

    • LOWPASS: remove high frequencies (gain_dB is not used).

    • HIGHPASS: remove low frequencies (gain_dB is not used).

    • BANDPASS: keep a frequency band (gain_dB is not used), not very easy to use because only center frequency is defined.

    • LOWSHELF: amplify of gain_dB low frequencies.

    • HIGHSHELF: amplify of gain_dB high frequencies.

  • steepnessByQorBW: biquad steepness may be defined by a quality factor Q (no unit, the bigger the steepest) or by a bandwidth BW (Hz); this parameter tells the steepness parameter type.

    • STEEPNESS_Q: steepness defined by quality factor.

    • STEEPNESS_BW: steepness defined by bandwidth.

  • steepness:

    • if steepnessByQorBW is STEEPNESS_Q, steepness parameter is a quality factor (typically 0.707 for -3dB/octave).

    • if steepnessByQorBW is STEEPNESS_BW, steepness parameter is a bandwidth in Hz.

  • centerCutoffFrequency: center frequency in Hz of the biquad.

  • gain_dB: gain in dB of the biquad (only for PEAKING, LOWSHELF, HIGHSHELF).

Grph output pin may be connected to a Graph-Viewer to show theoretical response curve (only when audio is started; it permits for instance to see impact of adding/removing a biquad.

Interleave

Overview

This document outlines the specifications for an audio processing block that interleaves multiple input streams into a single output stream. Each input can be mono or multichannel, but all inputs must have the same number of channels. The output stream will contain all channels from all input streams.

Please note that the primary function of this algorithm is to amalgamate several input streams into one cohesive output stream. It is not designed to alter the interleaving format of the individual samples within the stream; such transformations are the responsibility of the SFC (Sample Format Converter) algorithm.

Features

  • Multiple Inputs: Accepts up to 4 several audio input streams by default. The source code is delivered so that it can be changed to any value thru the algorithm capabilities:

    • Inside the file called audio_chain_interleave.c

    • Set the number of supported inputs to a different value. See the field called

    .iosIn.nb =AUDIO_CAPABILITY_CHUNK_ONE_TWO_THREE_FOUR,

  • Uniform Channel Inputs: Accepts multiple input streams with an equal number of channels. Compatible with both mono and multichannel formats, provided all inputs have the same channel count.

  • Interleaving: Merges channels from all inputs into one interleaved output stream.

  • Format conversion: Ability to change data format thanks to the SFC (Sample Format Converter) algorithm.

Inputs/Outputs

Inputs

  • Input Streams: Multiple audio input streams.

  • Source Format: The current format of the input audio samples is known thanks to the input pins that is aware of its own properties including data type and interleaving (see SFC documentation).

  • Target Format: The desired format for the output audio samples is known thanks to the output pin that is aware of its own properties data type and interleaving (see SFC documentation).

Output

  • Interleaved Audio Stream: A single audio output stream whose number of channels must be equal to sum of number of channels of input streams.

Processing Steps

Note: this algorithm encapsulates the SFC (Sample Format Converter) for input & output management. Please refer to its documentation.

  1. Input Handling: The block receives multiple audio input streams, each with the same number of channels.

  2. Interleaving & format conversion:

  • Channels from each input stream are interleaved one after the other. The process ensures that all the channels of each input are followed by all the channels of the next input, and so on.

  • Interleave supports following format conversion:

    1. interleaved into non interleaved samples and vice versa.

    2. Can convert from any of this data type to any other within this list: FIXED16, FIXED32, FLOAT, G711.

    3. Can convert input PDM LSB into PDM MSB and vice versa.

  • Interleave doesnt support the following format conversion:

    1. It cannot convert PCM to PDM data nor PDM into PCM data (see PDM2PCM algorithm for that).

    2. It cannot convert sampling frequency.

  1. Output Generation:
  • The final output stream is produced with all channels from all inputs interleaved.

Configuration Parameters

Apart for the format conversion, no parameter is needed, the block interleaves all the streams that are connected to the input pins.

The setting of the format conversion is handled by tuning the input & output pins according to the desired characteristics. Please refer to the SFC documentation.

Linear mix

Overview

The linear mixer linear-mix algorithm is the same algorithm as the mix but it has linear gain parameters instead of gains in decibels. The main advantage is to support negative gains allowing audio stream subtraction.

For more details, please refer to the mix algorithm dedicated documentation.

MDRC

Multi-band Dynamic Range Compressor and limiter.

MRDC has several tabs: General, Band 0, Band 1, Band 2, Band 3, Band 4, Limiter tabs.

General tab

  • preset: MDRC has today only one preset (Bass-boost).

  • mode:

    • bypass: no compressor, no limiter.
    • compressor only
    • limiter only
    • compressor, then limiter: compressor first (1 to 5 sub-band(s)), then limiter

  • numBands: number of sub-band(s); 1 to 5 sub-band(s)

Band <n> tab (n = 0 4), only band 0 numBands-1 tabs are active.

  • compressorFreqCutoff<n>: lower frequency (Hz) of sub-band n; fixed value 0 Hz for n=0, user defined for n>0; higher frequency of sub-band n is equal to lower frequency of sub-band n+1; last sub-band (n=numBands-1) higher frequency is equal to sampling frequency / 2.

  • compressorEnable<n>: enable or disable compressor for sub-band n.

  • attackTime<n>: attack time in ms.

  • releaseTime<n>: release time in ms

  • dynamicResponse<n>: user sets compressor dynamic response curve (input level (dB) in abscissa, output level (dB) in ordinate) adding points in the graph; when a point is selected, user can set an accurate numerical value using inputLevel/outputLevel boxes below the graph.

  • compressorPostGain<n>: output levels of dynamic response curve are negative in dB (maximum value is 0 dB); then a post gain is added to permit a bigger amplification of sub-band n.

How to add a point in the dynamicResponse curve

Adding a point in the graph is done by shift click on the curve followed by a pointer move (i.e move the mouse).

Remark: the button permits to copy the dynamicResponse<n> graph as an image.

Limiter tab

  • attackTime: attack time in ms.

  • releaseTime: release time in ms.

  • limiterThreshold: threshold in dB above which limiter is applied.

Mix

Mixer with API in dB. See linear-mix otherwise.

Overview

This document outlines the design and functionality of the audio processing block intended for mixing multiple input streams into a single output stream. The block applies a given gain to the various inputs to create a composite audio output.

Features

  • Multiple Inputs: Accepts several audio input streams, however they must have the same number of channels.

  • Mixing: Combines input streams into one output stream.

  • Gain Control: Adjusts the volume of individual input streams before mixing.

  • Format conversion: Ability to change data format.

Inputs/Outputs

Inputs

  • Input Streams: Multiple audio streams.

  • Volume control: A dedicated gain setting for every input.

  • Source Format: The current format of the input audio samples is known thanks to the input pins that are aware of its own properties including data type and interleaving (see SFC documentation).

  • Target Format: The desired format for the output audio samples is known thanks to the output pin that is aware of its own properties including data type and interleaving (see SFC documentation).

Output

  • Output Stream: A single audio output stream that is the sum of all adjusted input streams.

Processing Steps

  1. Input Handling: Each input stream is received by the audio processing block.

  2. Gain control:

    1. The gain parameter for each input is applied to adjust the volume level.

    2. Gain is converted from decibels to a linear scale before application.

  3. Summing:

    1. The gain-adjusted input streams are summed together.

    2. The mixer ensures that the combined signal does not exceed the maximum; it clips signal.

  4. Output Generation:

  • The final mixed audio stream is delivered as the composite of all inputs with applied gains.

Configuration Parameters

There are two types of parameters:

  • Format information for conversion is retrieved from the pins so that it is up to the user to configure the wires according to his desire.

  • The gain is a parameter which UI is provided as a tuning box and a slider.

Mono2Stereo

Mono to stereo converter

Features

  • Input: Accepts all PCM format, nbChannels must be equal to 1.

  • Output: Accepts all PCM format, nbChannels must be equal to 2.

  • Format conversion: Ability to change data format.

Inputs/Outputs

Inputs

  • Input Stream: A single audio input mono stream.

  • balance: balance between left & right output channels, between -1 (all left), 0 (duplicate input signal without gain modification into left & right channels) and +1 (all right)

    • left output channel gain = 1 if balance < 0, (1-balance) if balance > 0

    • right output channel gain = 1 if balance > 0, (1+balance) if balance < 0

  • Source Format: The current format of the input audio samples is known thanks to the input pins that are aware of its own properties including data type and interleaving (see SFC documentation).

  • Target Format: The desired format for the output audio samples is known thanks to the output pin that is aware of its own properties including data type and interleaving (see SFC documentation).

Output

  • Output Stream: A single audio output stereo stream.

Processing Steps

  1. Input Handling: input stream is received by the audio processing block.

  2. Gain control:

    1. Left & right output channels gain application according to balance as explained above.

Configuration Parameters

There are two types of parameters:

  • Format information for conversion is retrieved from the pins so that it is up to the user to configure the wires according to his desire.

  • The balance is a parameter which UI is provided as a tuning box and a slider.

NLMS

Normalized-LMS

Overview

This document describes the Normalized-LMS algorithm in LiveTune. This block is wrapping the CMSIS-DSP Normalized-LMS function. Please find the documentation here:

https://arm-software.github.io/CMSIS-DSP/latest/group__LMS__NORM.html

Inputs/Outputs

Inputs

  • Src: input data.

  • Ref: reference data

  • Echo length: Maximal removable echo (in seconds). The number of coefficients is determined from this input: numTaps = echo_length * sampling_frequency;

  • Adaptation Step size: It is the step size that controls filter coefficient updates; the biggest, the fastest convergence but the less accurate.

Output

  • Out: output data:

    • It is the filtered input signal.

  • Err: error data

    • It is the (Reference signal filtered input signal).

NR

Noise Reductor

NR algo is a stationary noise reductor; it tries to estimate SNR (Signal to Noise Ratio) by sub-band and apply a gain1 (or attenuation) in each sub-band depending on this SNR estimation and on a VAD estimation (also dependent on SNR of every sub-bands).

This algorithm assumes noise is stationary (slowly varying in time); it will be less efficient if noise is changing quickly (it will take some time to converge to a new noise model).

  • maxAttInNoise: maximum attenuation (in dB) by sub-band when NR algo decides that this sub-band is noisy; the bigger, the more noise attenuation with higher risk of lower naturalness.

  • maxAttInSpeech: maximum attenuation (in dB) by sub-band when NR algo decide that this sub-band is mainly speech (should be < maxAttInNoise).

  • noiseMeanRef: reference average noise threshold (in dB) for min gain estimation; when average noise is below this threshold, NR computed attenuation is lowered to keep better naturalness.

  • lowPassBandPcent: when signal is very noisy, NR may generate high frequency annoying artefacts (like whistles), this parameter permits in such cases to filter high frequencies and thus remove these artefacts; this parameter is expressed in percentage of the full-band signal (i.e.sampling frequency / 2); when signal is clean, the low-pass filter is not applied to preserve voice clarity.

  • convergenceProfile: noise estimation speed.

    • default: good choice in most cases (for not too noisy signals).

    • fast: faster convergence at the risk of wrong noise estimation.

    • accurate : more accurate noise estimation but slower convergence.

    • user defined with alpha: convergence through alphaB & alphaG parameters below.

  • alphaB and alphaG (only when convergenceProfile is set to user defined with alpha): these 2 parameters permit to define a per sub-band noise learning curve quite difficult to explain depending on SNR estimation and permitting to evaluate current SNR depending on previous SNR and new signal and thus to evaluate noise level of current sub-band. Lowering these alpha parameters accelerate noise estimation; user should try different values (separately for alphaB & alphaG) to understand impact on noise estimation speed and accuracy for its use-case.

PDM2PCM

Features

  • Input: Accepts only PDM (LSB first or MSB first) format.

  • Output: Accepts all PCM format

  • Format conversion: Ability to change data format.

Inputs/Outputs

Inputs

  • Input Stream: A single audio input stream.

  • from_i2s: a checkbox telling if PDM data comes from I2S or not (if it comes from I2S, knowing that I2S data registers are 16 bits, in case of mono signal, changing the bit order on the I2S configuration will result in a temporal switch of two consecutive samples; thus the algo must know it to compensate this temporal switch)

  • high_pass_tap: high pass coefficient (floating-point value), between 0 and 1 (the closest to 1, the steepest filter response; no high-pass filter if equal to 0)

  • gain: gain in dB

  • Source Format: The format for the input audio samples is known thanks to the input pin that is aware of its own properties.

  • Target Format: The desired format for the output audio samples is known thanks to the output pin that is aware of its own properties.

Output

  • Output Stream: A single audio output stream.

Processing Steps

  1. Input Handling: input stream is received by the audio processing block.

  2. pdm2pcm decoding:

    1. decoding according to input vs output data types.

Configuration Parameters

There are two types of parameters:

  • Format information for conversion is retrieved from the pins so that it is up to the user to configure the wires according to his desire (input vs output data types).

  • The parameters provided as a tuning box; see https://www.st.com/resource/en/user_manual/um2372-stm32cube-pdm2pcm-software-library-for-the-stm32f4f7h7-series-stmicroelectronics.pdf for further details

Resample

.

Overview

The resample algorithm aim is to convert signal sampling frequency. It can do up or down sampling with integer or fractional resampling ratio.

Features

  • Sampling frequency conversion:

    • Supports up and down sampling with integer or fractional resampling ratio.

    • It can convert from any sampling frequency in the range 8000, 12000, 16000, 24000, 32000, 48000 Hz to any sampling frequency in the same frequency range.

    • It supports different filtering types:

      • IIR:

        • HPF_TYPE_BUTTERWORTH,

        • HPF_TYPE_CHEBYSHEV1,

        • HPF_TYPE_CHEBYSHEV2,

        • HPF_TYPE_ELLIPTIC,

      • FIR (not provided by default to offer memory for other use case, can be activated for compilation setting the define USE_HPF_TYPE_FIR)

        • HPF_TYPE_PARKSMCCLELLAN,

        • HPF_TYPE_KAISERWINDOW,

  • Format conversion: Ability to change data format.

Inputs/Outputs

Inputs

  • Input Stream: Input audio stream.

  • Filtering Type: Selection of IIR or FIR (see Features list section).

  • Source Sampling Frequency: It is known thanks to the input pin that is aware of its own properties including data type and frequency (see following figure).

  • Target Sampling Frequency: It is known thanks to the output pin that is aware of its own properties data type and frequency (see following figure).

  • Source Format: The current format of the input audio samples is known thanks to the input pin that is aware of its own properties including data type and interleaving (see SFC documentation).

  • Target Format: The desired format for the output audio samples is known thanks to the output pin that is aware of its own properties data type and interleaving (see SFC documentation).

Output

  • Output Stream: A single audio output stream that is the input one at the request sampling frequency and formatted according to requested Target Format.

Processing Information

The only resample configuration parameter is the filter type used for resampling; resample uses low-pass filters and several banks of filter with different filter design methods have been included in resample algo, each of these design methods have its pro & cons in terms of MHz/memory consumption (decreasing consumption order: Butterworth, Chebyshev1/Chebyshev2, elliptic), response curve (see https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Signals_and_Systems/Filter_Implementations and https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elliptic_filter for more details).

Configuration Parameters

There are two types of parameters:

  • Format information for conversion is retrieved from the pins so that it is up to the user to configure the wires according to his desire:

    • Sampling frequencies

    • Interleaving.

    • Data types (fixed, float, etc.).

  • The Filtering type is a parameter which UI is provided as a drop list.

Overview

This document outlines the design and functionality of the audio processing block intended for routing multiple input channels into a single output stream. The block selectively combines channels from various inputs to create a composite audio output.

Features

Overview

This document describes an audio front end which aims at boosting voice recognition performances in a noisy environment. The processing is done in the frequency domain.

Features

  • This specific algorithm is hard coded for input streams of 129 bands. The WOLA algorithms must be tuned accordingly.

SFC

Samples Format Converter

.

Overview

This document provides a concise overview of an audio format conversion block designed to convert audio samples from one data type to another. The block supports various audio sample formats, including fixed-point 16-bit (fixed16), fixed-point 32-bit (fixed32), floating-point (float), and G.711 encoded data. It also supports PDM domain data and allows to convert the stream from MSB to LSB first. Additionally, it can handle the conversion of audio data between interleaved and non-interleaved formats.

The sfc is an essential tool for audio processing applications that require flexibility in handling different audio sample formats and interleaving options. By providing a straightforward interface for specifying the source and target formats, this block simplifies the process of audio data conversion for developers and audio engineers. It is widely used inside AudioChain and is also part of many algorithms so that they offer a wide range of input and output format capabilities. The downside may be that if the user doesnt take good care, he may end up making a lot of useless conversions.

Features

  • Multiple Format Support:

    • PCM domain: Converts between fixed16, fixed32, float, and G.711 encoded formats.

    • PDM domain: Converts between MSB & LSB first.

  • Interleaving Conversion: Transforms audio data between interleaved and non-interleaved formats.

  • Bit Depth Conversion: Changes the bit depth of audio samples.

  • Gain Control: Apply a gain given in dB.

  • Note that it does not support:

    • Sample Rate Conversion, see the resample algorithm for that matter.

    • Time to frequency domain conversion, see the WOLA algorithm for that matter.

Inputs/Outputs

Inputs

  • Gain value: Decibels

  • Audio Data: The input audio samples to be converted. Multiple channels supported.

  • Source Format: The current format of the input audio samples is known thanks to the input pin that is aware of its own properties including data type and interleaving as shown by next figure.

  • Target Format: The desired format for the output audio samples is known thanks to the output pin that is aware of its own properties data type and interleaving as shown by next figure.

Output

  • Converted Audio Data: The audio samples in the target format and interleaving option with chosen gain.

Configuration Parameters

As shown in previous figure, there are two types of parameters:

  • Format information is retrieved from the pins so that it is up to the user to configure the wires according to his desire.

  • The gain is a more classical parameter which has a tuning box and a slider inside the sfc box to allow its setting.

Sound-font

Sound-font description.

A SoundFont (.sf2 file) is a type of audio file used for storing digital audio samples and associated instrument parameters. These files are designed to be used with MIDI synthesizers and software that support the SoundFont format. The SoundFont element allows playing an SF2 file flashed in the external memory, then plays keys using instrument presets. The Player is a generator and can be connected to any other element compatible with its chunk, such as a Faust reverb, viewer, etc.

Notice: This Element uses the external flash to load SF2 files.

The SF2 file needs to be packaged with a file signature and a file size. If the signature is missing, the element will not work and will report an issue in the log terminal. The SF2 packaging should be done using a bash script. When you execute the script Middlewares/ST/Audio-Kit/Tools/SoundFont.sh, you will be invited to select a board and an SF2 file. You must select an SF2 file compatible with the boards performance.

SoundFont.sh bash script.

The folder includes 2 free SF2 files coming from: https://musical-artifacts.com/artifacts?formats=sf2&tags=florestan

To be fully compliant with a standard MIDI file, the SF2 must be fully compliant with the General MIDI (GM) specifications.

  • https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_MIDI

The General MIDI specification details a set of presets along with an audio rendering specification.

The MIDI file could also be used for other use cases such as:

  • Drum machine.

  • Sample player.

  • Events controller

  • High-quality virtual keyboard.

  • Etc.

This is why there are so many flavors of SF2 you can download from the web. The limitation is a compromise between SF2 memory space and sound rendering quality. An SF2s size could vary from 200 Kilobytes to 500 Megabytes.

When you convert an SF2 using SoundFont.sh, the script will print the RAM and the flash memory required to run presets in yellow.

Here are some places where you can find free SF2 files for testing:

  • https://musical-artifacts.com

  • https://archive.org/download/free-soundfonts-sf2-2019-04

  • https://sites.google.com/site/soundfonts4u

Using Sound-font in LiveTune

A Simple dataflow using Sound-Font

There are 4 controls:

Table: Sequencer https://signal.vercel.app/edit
Gate Allows to test a preset, to simulate a keyboard key, The button produce a note on and note off at the button up using the selected preset (the gate latency is huge)
Preset Allows to select a preset or a note from 0 to 128 and you can test it using the Gate.
Midi Drum Kit Given drums have a single note, the GM specifies that channel 10 plays a drum instrument using its note. For example, the note 51 (Eb4/D#4) on the channel 10 plays a instrument Ride Cymbal 1 and a note 60 (C5 (middle C)) on the channel 10 plays instrument aHi Bongo
SoundFontPtr It is the address used by Sound-font element to load the .sf2 file. Notice you cannot modify this SF2 Address: To simplify the interface, within LiveTune the address is not modifiable, but you can in a generated project.

Performance consideration:

The MIDI format allows up to 16 channels to be played simultaneously. A channel can play an instrument using several operators and processing, but the CPU load is not equivalent for all instruments. Some require multiple samples and more complex mathematics computed using double-precision floating points.

  • The SoundFont is stored in the external flash. The external flash is not as fast as the internal flash and could exhibit significant latency depending on the MCU family and the flash chip mounted on the board. The CPU load displayed at the bottom of LiveTune can help you to check the CPU load consumed by the playback. The audio output frequency could also impact the performance mandatory for the playback.

For example, an H5 has drastically less RAM than an H7 and no external RAM. The H5 has a single-precision FPU, meaning that all mathematical operations using double precision will be computed by the CPU rather than the FPU. Furthermore, the H5s CPU frequency is roughly half that of the H7. This implies that the H5 can be used for MIDI playback, but not for all use cases.

Example use cases:

  • Example of Sound-Font files:

    • For the H5:

      • florestan-subset_for_h5.sf2: number of presets reduced to fit the H5 ram memory.

    • For other fast MCUs:

      • florestan-full.sf2 or any others

  • Example of midi-file

    • midiFiles/venture.mid

Consequently, to play a MIDI file properly, the MCU must meet the playback performance requirements.

Midi device routing

To master the connection between midi device you need a MIDI router, it can be software or hardware. The device name could change, it can be called Midi host or Midi Controller by different manufacturers, but the role is equivalent. A MIDI router is a device or software that manages and directs MIDI data between MIDI-enabled devices. MIDI, which stands for Musical Instrument Digital Interface, is a technical standard that allows electronic musical instruments, computers, and other related devices to communicate and synchronize with each other. The Midi router could route Midi messages to an USB transport or the traditional Midi socket.

  • Most of the PC Midi tools have a midi routing function to connect a Midi port In to a Midi port Out. Such as MPC Beat from AKAI

  • Here is an example of HW Midi router device

  • Alternatively, for a quick test, you can use a web midi router such as https://midi-router.tsoop.com allowing to connect a device to he Stm32board running Sound Font.

  • To directly connect a MIDI device to another device, one of them must take the role of router (MIDI host). This case is not supported in Audio Kit. However, there are some reference projects on GitHub. https://github.com/rppicomidi/usb_midi_host implements this feature and using TinyUSB (the USB API used by Audio kit). This feature could be easily adapted to Audio Kit.

Split

Overview

This document describes an audio processing block designed to split a single input audio stream into multiple identical output streams. This splitter block is intended to distribute the same audio data to various processing units or signal paths, ensuring that each receives an exact copy of the input.

Note: It is mandatory to use this block to distribute from a single output pin to several other input pins.

Features

  • Single Input Stream: Accepts one audio input stream to be replicated.

  • Multiple Outputs: Generates several output streams that are identical copies of the input.

  • Format Preservation: Retains the original sample rate and the channel configuration.

  • Format Conversion: Offers means to convert some characteristics of the signal: data type (fixed16, fixed32, float, etc), interleaving.

Inputs/Outputs

Inputs

  • Input Streams: The single audio input stream to be split.

  • Source Format: The current format of the input audio samples is known thanks to the input pins that is aware of its own properties including data type and interleaving (see SFC documentation).

  • Target Format: The desired format for the output audio samples is known thanks to the output pin that is aware of its own properties data type and interleaving (see SFC documentation).

Output

  • Replicated Audio Streams: Multiple output streams that are replicas of the input stream. The replication is exact if Target and Source formats are equal.

Processing Steps

Note: this algorithm encapsulates the SFC for input & output management. Please refer to its documentation.

  • Input Reception: The block receives the input audio stream.

  • Signal Replication:

    • The input stream is duplicated into multiple streams.

    • Each output stream is a replica of the input, with no alterations if Target and Source formats are equal. If Target and Source formats are different, the audio data remain the same but in a new shape (can be floating point from a fixed16 input stream or any other conversion that SFC can handle)

  • Output Distribution:

    • The replicated streams are routed to their respective outputs.

Configuration Parameters

Apart for the format conversion, no parameter is needed, the block interleaves all the streams that are connected to the input pins.

The setting of the format conversion is handled by tuning the input & output pins according to the desired characteristics. Please refer to the SFC documentation.

Stereo2Mono

Stereo to mono converter

Features

  • Input: Accepts all PCM format, nbChannels must be equal to 2.

  • Output: Accepts all PCM format, nbChannels must be equal to 1.

  • Format conversion: Ability to change data format.

Inputs/Outputs

Inputs

  • Input Stream: A single audio input stereo stream.

  • balance: balance between left & right input channels, between -1 (only left), 0 (average of left & right channels) and +1 (only right)

    • left input channel gain = 0.5*(1-balance)

    • right input channel gain = 0.5*(1+balance)

  • Source Format: The current format of the input audio samples is known thanks to the input pins that are aware of its own properties including data type and interleaving (see SFC documentation).

  • Target Format: The desired format for the output audio samples is known thanks to the output pin that is aware of its own properties including data type and interleaving (see SFC documentation).

Output

  • Output Stream: A single audio output mono stream.

Processing Steps

  1. Input Handling: input stream is received by the audio processing block.

  2. Gain control:

    1. Left & right input channels gain application according to balance as explained above.

Configuration Parameters

There are two types of parameters:

  • Format information for conversion is retrieved from the pins so that it is up to the user to configure the wires according to his desire.

  • The balance is a parameter which UI is provided as a tuning box and a slider.

WOLA

Weighted OverLap and Add (forward and invert)

.

Overview

Weighted Overlap-Add (WOLA) is a method for transforming audio signals between the time and frequency domains and vice versa. The WOLA method is an extension of the Overlap-Add (OLA) method, which is used to process long or streaming audio signals in chunks. WOLA incorporates a windowing function to reduce artifacts at the boundaries of the processed blocks, improving the quality of the reconstructed signal.

This algorithm is split in 2 algos wolaFwd & wolaInv:

  • wolaFwd (WOLA forward) for conversion from time to frequency domain which uses the FFT (Fast Fourier Transform)

  • wolaInv (WOLA inverse) for conversion from frequency to time domain which uses the IFFT (Inverse Fast Fourier Transform)

  • they are always used together since system input/output signals are only time domain signals.

It is useful when building chain of algorithms that work in the frequency (or spectral) domain (such as fBeamforming algo, i.e.frequency beamforming or fnlms, i.e.subbands NLMS algorithm, etc).

Features

Inputs/Outputs

Notes:

  • In the time domain, the number of samples is retrieved from the input or output streams (acChunk buses) through the nbElements field.

  • In the frequency domain, the number of bands is retrieved from the input or output streams (acChunk buses) through the nbElements field.

Inputs

  • WolaFwd Input Stream: mono or multichannel time domain data.

  • WolaInv Input Stream: mono or multichannel frequency domain data.

  • Number of samples and number of bands: the combination of these input/output streams properties permits to deduce the overlap ratio and the weighting window.

Output

  • WolaFwd Output Stream: mono or multichannel frequency domain data.

  • WolaInv Output Stream: mono or multichannel time domain data.

Frequency domain constraints in AudioChain/LiveTune

The constraints are the following ones:

  1. Format Constraint:

    1. AudioChain frequency domain processing only supports non interleaved floating points data.

  1. WolaFwd input number of samples constraint:

    1. WolaFwd consumes internally a power of 2 (i.e., 128, 256, 512, 1024, ) time domain samples for FFT reason and produces internally the same number of frequency domain samples.

    2. thus an overlap of successive input buffers (whose size may be any) is necessary.

    3. overlap ratio (deduced internally) permits to cope with this constraint.

  2. WolaFwd output number of bands constraint:

    1. Internal frequency domain samples are complex and conjugate-symmetric, thus only half of the frequency domain samples are enough to keep the full spectral representation of time domain signal.

    2. However, there is the need for one more element for the DC component.

    3. Hence number of bands must be a power of 2 (half of FFT size) plus 1 elements (i.e., 65, 129, 257, 513, ).

  3. WolaFwd & WolaInv dependency constraints:

    1. WolaFwd input buffer samples number and WolaInv output buffer samples number must be identical.

    2. WolaFwd output buffer bands number and WolaInv input buffer bands number must be identical.

  4. How overlap ratio and weighting windows are deduced internally:

    1. The overlap ratio is deduced from the input & output number of elements (samples in time domain & bands in frequency domain)

      overlap ratio=1-number of samples/(2*(number of bands-1))

    2. a minimum overlap ratio of 25% is needed, thus some input vs output configurations wrt the number of samples/bands will be rejected if this overlap ratio constraint is not respected.

      1-number of samples/(2*(number of bands-1)) > 0.25

      number of samples/(2*(number of bands-1)) < 0.75

      number of samples < 0.75*(2*(number of bands-1))

      number of samples < 1.5*(number of bands-1)

    3. The window is then chosen to comply with COLA constraint, i.e.sum of shifted by number of samples weighting windows is equal to 1.

    4. Overall weighting window may be split between analysis (WolaFwd) and synthesis (WolaInv): see synthesisWindow configuration parameter below

Processing Steps

The WOLA processing block consists of the following stages:

  • WolaFwd

    1. Windowing (analysis windowing).

    2. Block Processing: Organize the windowed signal into overlapping blocks.

    3. FFT: Compute the FFT of each block to obtain frequency-domain representation.

  • WolaInv

    1. Inverse FFT (IFFT): Convert the processed blocks back to the time domain.

    2. Windowing (synthesis windowing), if synthesisWindow parameter enabled.

    3. Overlap-Add: Combine the overlapping time-domain blocks to reconstruct the signal.

Configuration Parameters

wolaFwd and wolaInv configuration is done through:

  1. synthesisWindow.

synthesisWindow

Mind that the same value (enabled or disabled) must be set for both WolaFwd & WolaInv.

If synthesisWindow is disabled, no windowing is applied by WolaInv. However the WolaFwd still applies its analysis windowing.

If synthesisWindow is enabled, the windowing is applied by both WolaFwd & WolaInv (in such case, the combination of analysis window and synthesis window is equal to synthesisWindow disableds analysis window)

If algorithms inserted in between wolaFwd and wolaInv are linear algorithms and dont combine different signals, using synthesisWindow is useless. On the contrary, synthesisWindow is mandatory else the wolaInv will produce annoying audio artefacts (see https://www.dsprelated.com/freebooks/sasp/Weighted_Overlap_Add.html). As an example, fBeamforming and fnlms algorithms are doing linear processing but they combine different signals thus synthesisWindow must be enabled.

These analysis/synthesis windows and associated overlap ratio computed by WOLA algo insure optimal signal reconstruction for time domain frequency domain time domain transformation.

Overlap Ratio

As explained in the chapter called Frequency domain constraints in AudioChain/LiveTune, the overlap ratio is deduced from the input and output acChunks.

Following figure illustrates a case with an overlap ratio of 50%:

  • The wolaFwd input is a time domain signal with 128 samples of 16 kHz (8 ms)

  • The wolaFwd output is a frequency domain signal with 129 bands (first bin is for DC component). In this example, for simplicity, this is also the input of the WolaInv

  • The wolaInv output is a time domain signal with 128 samples of 16 kHz (8 ms)

  • Constraints explained in the chapter called Frequency domain constraints in AudioChain/LiveTune are respected,

Message Viewer

The message element is used for debugging purposes, it allows to display a text formatted by another element and sent it through pin acMsg. The message element has two displays, one for the text and one for the watch variables.

Panels will be visible only if data are sent to the element.

Text Display:

You can extract a snipped of text using the copy/past mechanism.

  • The Copy button allows to copy the complete text buffer and variable snapshot in the clipboard.

  • The Stop/Continue button allows to freeze the text scrolling.

  • The Clear button allows to erase the text buffer.

Implementation:

The communication between the element and the message viewer is done using a Json string.

{
   "Signature": "acMsg",
   "Title": "Text",
   "From": "rms-1",
   "To": "Message-Viewer-1",
   "Vars": "ch0:-4.8dB ch1:-4.8dB",
   "Text": "channel 0: 0.58% = -4.8 dB\nchannel 1: 0.58% = -4.8 dB\n"
}

Json record

Json fields:

All other extra fields in the Json record will be ignored.

Vars and Text fields are optional.

  • If the Vars field is not present in the record, the viewer wont show it, same.

  • If the Text field is not present in the record, the viewer wont show it, same.

Signature Always acMsg
Title Just an id used internally
From Name instance of the element sender
To Name instance of the element viewer
Vars A string json Text encoded Key: Value separated by a space
Text Any text as string json Text encoded

Json fields

The element plugin_processing_rms.c is the perfect example implementing a both messages and variable transmissions.

Typically, a LiveTune plugin will use the livetune_send_block_text_async () function to send a payload to a message viewer element.

This low-level function sends a Json string using a signature. We can add optional some extra Json fields as a string and a text body.

So, we use this Prototype:

pText message text as string hello world
pExtra routing and variables as json From:rms-1,To:Message-Viewer-1,Vars:hello:world 
/**
* @brief Send a json string to Livetune (asynchronous transmission)
* @param pSignature  type of message
* @param pTitle      title or id
* @param pExtra      title extra fields as text to concatenate to the json string, pExtra could be null
* @param pText       the text body in the field "Text:", pText could be null
*/

uint32_t livetune_send_block_text_async(uint8_t bForce, const char_t *pSignature, char_t *pTitle, char_t *pExtra, char_t *pText)

How to send a message to the element message view.

pExtra="From":"rms-1","To":"Message-Viewer-1","Vars":"ch0:-4.8dB ch1:-4.8dB";
pText= Hello world;
livetune_send_block_text_async(FALSE, "acMsg", "Text", pExtra, pText);
